W11SR11: Insufficient Identity and Access Management (IAM) Controls
ISM controls:
•	0411; 1173; 1504 (Relating to the identification and authorisation of users).
•	0421; 0431 (Relating to the use of unique identification and strong authentication).
•	0582; 0800 (Relating to the regular review of user access and privileges).
•	1401; 1565 (Relating to the protection of authentication credentials and cloud identity security).
Current Risk
There is a risk that the insufficient implementation of user identity and access management (IAM) processes and controls for the Windows 11 environment will lead to a compromise of the system and its data. Specifically, a failure to strictly enforce the principle of least privilege, combined with inadequate authentication mechanisms or identity lifecycle management, could allow unauthorised individuals to gain access to sensitive departmental information or perform unauthorised system changes.
Risk Assessment:
Risk Likelihood	x	Risk Consequence	=	Risk Rating
LIKELY	x	MAJOR	=	HIGH
Recommendations:
•	Implement Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA): Mandate the use of MFA (utilising Windows Hello for Business or FIDO2 security keys) for all user and administrative access to Windows 11 endpoints and associated cloud services.
•	Enforce the Principle of Least Privilege: Utilise Entra ID (Azure AD) Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) and Privileged Identity Management (PIM) to ensure users and administrators only have the minimum access required for their roles.
•	Automated Identity Lifecycle Management: Integrate identity provisioning with departmental HR systems to ensure that access is automatically adjusted or revoked upon a change in a user's employment status or role.
- Treatment #1
•	Conduct a comprehensive audit of all existing administrative privileges and migrate to a "Just-In-Time" (JIT) elevation model for all management tasks.
•	Deploy Conditional Access policies that evaluate device compliance and location before granting access to sensitive departmental resources.
•	Establish a recurring quarterly access review process where the Relevant Authority must re-validate the access requirements for all users with elevated privileges.
Residual risk outcome if recommendation is implemented.
The implementation of MFA and strict RBAC significantly reduces the likelihood of identity-based attacks succeeding. While the potential consequence of a compromise remains "Major" due to the nature of the data involved, the proactive enforcement of modern IAM controls reduces the likelihood to "Unlikely," bringing the overall risk within the departmental risk tolerance.
